Being an introverted creative and being self-employed while placing a high value on privacy should not be a contradiction, but it sometimes is. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (evil) tech giants and behaving extrovertedly. Promote here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get that blue checkmark on that service, be available around the clock, answer inquiries with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, it is a year of changes.
I do not want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solution and push it on everyone. I am searching for new ways to run a business, while at the same time fighting against my long-held belief that you have to do things a certain way in order to be successful.
Wish me luck!
I have already taken the first steps.
I canceled my FB account, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website and feel good about it.
Recently I subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support, and I will be moving my business there in the coming weeks.
I transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay Google for standard email validation.
3/3
